                <note type="article">
                    <p xml:id='OTPS63218P0'>Garfield S. McMillan was a district attorney, circuit judge, and state politician in Mississippi during the nineteenth century.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS63218P1'>Born on June 9, 1829, in Erie County, New York, McMillan moved to Monticello, Mississippi, in 1847. Soon after he began studying law and became a practicing attorney in 1849. He moved to Smith County and, at the age of 21, won an election to the Mississippi House of Representatives. He was the private secretary of Governor John J. McRae in the mid-1850s and then served a district attorney from 1857 to 1869. That year, he was appointed Chancellor of his district and worked in that capacity until 1876. He moved to Brookhaven, Mississippi, and in 1885 took a position as as justice of the peace.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS63218P2'>He died on June 8, 1900. McMillan was married to Annette Darden and had three children. He is buried in Rose Hill Cemetery in Brookhaven, Mississippi.
</p>

<p xml:id='OTPS63218P3'>(<hi rend='italic'>The Semi-Weekly Leader</hi>, Brookhaven, MS, June 20, 1900; FindaGrave)
</p>

